defaultWritten Evidence from the Directory of Social Change [CEP0013]default&#xa0;defaultAbout the Directory of Social ChangedefaultThe Directory of 
defaultSocial Change (DSC) has a vision of an independent voluntary sector at the heart of social change. We believe that the activities of charities and other voluntary organisations are crucial to the health of our society.
defaultThrough our publications, courses and
default conferences, we come in contact with thousands of organisations each year. The majority are small to medium-sized, rely on volunteers and are constantly struggling to maintain and improve the services they provide.
defaultWe are not a membership body. Our public
default commentary and the policy positions we take are based on clear principles, and are informed by the contact we have with these organisations. We also undertake campaigns on issues that affect them or which evolve out of our research.
defaultWe view our role as th
defaultat of a ‘concerned citizen’, acting as a champion on behalf of the voluntary sector in its widest sense. We ask critical questions, challenge the prevailing view, and try to promote debate on issues we consider to be important.
default&#xa0;
defaultIntroductiondefaultRecent debate 
defaultin the media on the matter of charity Chief Executive pay has not reflected the reality for the vast majority of charities in the UK. Nor has it been put into context with other organisations (for example in the public or private sector) and how th
defaultey remun
defaulterate senior managers for comparable levels of responsibility.
defaultIn fact, some of the statements made 
defaultappear to be based on 
defaulta misunderstanding of the facts
default – for example the phrase ‘charity boardroom pay’
default is a misrepresentation
default. 
defaultIn fact a miniscule number of
default trustees are paid for their role and probably well over 90% perform their duties on an entirely voluntary basis.
defaultThis
default debate 
defaultis clearly of public interest but it is vital that it is 
defaultinformed by facts
default, 
defaultevidence,
default and context,
default not conjecture, speculation and
default media hype. Otherwise unjustified damage to public trust and confidence in 
defaultall charities (not just those with ‘highly pa
defaulti
defaultd’ CEOs
default)
default may result. Below we draw together some key facts and information with the aim of informing discussion and debate about the i
defaultssue.
